Test suite for Pass B type-set expansion (the `%t` type-slot mechanism), covering `expand_types_one`, `build_type_set`, and `expand_dict`, ported from `test/types.test.ts`. Exercises both a synthetic fixed type set and the real `dict.steno` corpus.

The synthetic fixture in `opts()` defines four types: `TPH` (number, arity 0), `STR` (string, arity 0), `PR` (`Promise<%t>`, arity 1), `PH` (`Map<%t, %t>`, arity 2), with `generic_args` restricted to just number/string — this bounds the combinatorial expansion so exact chain lengths are assertable. `chain_count_and_uniqueness` encodes the expected chain size formula: `1 (base) + 2 (arity-0 leaves) + 3 (Promise: head + 1 arg-filled non-terminal... wait per test comment, Promise contributes head+full = treated as "3") + 7 (Map: head + one-arg + full combinations)` — the literal numbers `1+2+3+7` are load-bearing and will silently drift if `opts()`'s type list or `generic_args` change; whoever edits the fixture must recompute this sum.

Key mechanics asserted here that aren't obvious from `steno`'s public API alone: arity-0 types always produce a single terminal `TypedEntry`; arity-N generics produce a chain of N+1 entries per combination where all but the last are non-terminal, and intermediate (non-final) steps render arguments space-separated without angle brackets or commas (e.g. `"Map string"` for the one-arg step of a 2-arity type), only becoming `Map<string, number>` at the fully-terminal step. Stroke paths are built by appending `/STROKE` segments (e.g. `X/PH/STR/TPH`) and must stay unique across the whole chain — `chain_count_and_uniqueness` checks this invariant directly.

`construct(template) -> Option<Vec<TypedEntry>>` is the core test helper: wraps a template in a fake `````X\n...\n```` ``` chunk, runs it through `parse_source` → `expand_counts` → `expand_types_one` against the fixed `opts()`, and returns the first entry's expansion chain. `corpus_entries()` reads `dict.steno` relative to `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR` at `../../dict.steno` — this is a real, evolving dictionary file, so `corpus_type_set`, `corpus_expands_end_to_end`, `corpus_deep_terminal_type_entry`, and `corpus_free_type_tabstop` are coupled to its current contents; if entries for `STKWR-PBGS/PH-FLT/STR/TPH` or `STKWR-PBGS/SKP-FLT` are renamed/removed in `dict.steno`, or if the type set gains/loses `@noarg` types, these tests break. `corpus_type_set` specifically hardcodes "14 arity-0 types minus 4 @noarg (null/undefined/never/function) = 10" and confirms `never` (`STPHR`) is deliberately not culled despite superficially resembling the other filtered-out types.

`corpus_free_type_tabstop` demonstrates that free/generic types (`SKP`) get their own tabstop slot in the template (shown as `%3`) distinct from the argument tabstops (`%0`, `%1`, `%2`), while the parameter name keeps `%0` — this is the "free_type" flag's visible effect, contrasted with the fixed `TypeDef`s built via `def()` which all set `free_type: false`.